# Documentation (mandatory with features)

**Do not ship user-facing features without updating docs in the same branch/PR.**

## Two audiences

| Audience | Where | When to update |
|----------|-------|----------------|
| **Users / GitHub visitors** | Root `README.md` | New capabilities, download/install changes, tagline-level positioning |
| **Developers / agents** | `docs/` | Architecture, roadmap, competitive notes, fitness PRD, launch checklists |

## When this applies

Update docs when the change affects **what users see or do**:

- New tabs, dialogs, charts, or logging flows
- New life categories (defaults) or fitness programs
- New build/install paths or data locations
- Roadmap-tier features (encryption, sync, AI) — even partial/shipped slices

**Skip** for internal refactors, test-only changes, or bug fixes with no user-visible behavior change.

## What to do (same PR as the feature)

1. **README.md** — add a bullet under **Features** when behavior is user-visible
2. **docs/architecture.md** — if modules, schema, or data flow changed
3. **docs/ROADMAP.md** — check off items or add phases when shipping roadmap work
4. **docs/GITHUB_LAUNCH.md** — only if release process changes
5. **programs/*.json** — document source in JSON `source` field when adding official tables

## README policy

| Do | Don't |
|----|--------|
| Update Features, Download, Roadmap summary | Rewrite tagline or license casually |
| Link to `docs/ROADMAP.md` for detail | Put implementation detail in README |
| Keep install steps accurate for exe + source | Document every bug fix |

## Agent checklist before calling work done

- [ ] User-visible? → README Features bullet / “What you get” row
- [ ] Schema or module layout changed? → `docs/architecture.md`
- [ ] Roadmap item shipped? → `docs/ROADMAP.md` checkbox
- [ ] New program? → `programs/` JSON + fitness tests
- [ ] No secrets or `data/` in the commit

## Release rebuild / push gate

When the human asks to **rebuild, version, and push** a release:

1. Run the README Features gate in `.cursor/rules/build-release.mdc` **before** tagging
2. Do not treat CHANGELOG alone as enough — GitHub visitors read `README.md` first
3. Hotfix-only releases may skip README edits only when there is truly no user-visible delta (state that explicitly)
